-- India’s Rupee, Bonds Decline as Inflation Forecast to Accelerate
-- B y   J e a n e t t e   R o d r i g u e s
-- 2013-11-12T04:32:04Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-12/india-s-rupee-bonds-decline-as-inflation-forecast-to-accelerate.html
India ’s rupee dropped to an eight-week low and bonds fell before a report that economists forecast
will show inflation accelerated last month.  Consumer prices  rose 9.90 percent in October from a year
earlier, after a 9.84 percent increase in September, according
to the median of 32 estimates in a Bloomberg survey before data
due after the market shuts today. The rupee is also weakening as
global investors sell Indian debt and favor the dollar on signs
of a recovery in the  U.S. economy , according to Religare Capital
Markets Ltd.  “With inflationary pressures rising, we do not rule out
the possibility of another 25 basis point” hike in the
repurchase rate by March, said Tirthankar Patnaik, a strategist
at Religare in Mumbai. The timing of a paring of U.S. stimulus
“will be the key to the rupee’s movement in the next couple of
months,” he said.  The rupee fell 0.4 percent to 63.4800 per dollar as of 9:51
a.m. in Mumbai, according to prices from local banks compiled by
Bloomberg. It touched 63.5150 earlier, the weakest level since
Sept. 17. The currency dropped 3.8 percent in the past month as
the Bloomberg  Dollar Index , which tracks the greenback against
10 major counterparts, climbed 1 percent.  The yield on the 7.16 percent government bonds due May 2023
rose nine basis points, or 0.09 percentage point, to 9.04
percent, according to prices from the central bank’s trading
system. The rate climbed as high as 9.14 percent yesterday, the
highest level since Aug. 19.  Volatility, Forwards  Global funds sold more Indian bonds than they bought every
day last week, exchange data show. A Nov. 8 U.S. government
report showed payrolls increased 204,000 in October, almost
twice as much as economists predicted in a Bloomberg survey.  Government data today will show industrial production rose
3.5 percent in September from a year earlier after a 0.6 percent
gain the previous month, according to the median of 37 estimates
in a separate Bloomberg survey.  A report yesterday showed
exports rose and imports fell in October.  One-month implied volatility in the rupee, a gauge of
expected moves in the  exchange rate  used to price options,
climbed 45 basis points to 13.56 percent.  Three-month onshore rupee forwards dropped 0.3 percent to
65.06 per dollar, data compiled by Bloomberg show. Offshore non-deliverable contracts declined 0.3 percent to 65.39. Forwards
are agreements to buy or sell assets at a set price and date.
Non-deliverable contracts are settled in dollars.  To contact the reporter on this story:
